Around here I   like to   say that every bad thing that a public company do=
es is also securities fraud. It does the bad thing, it does not immediately=
 tell shareholders about the bad thing, later the shareholders find out abo=
ut the bad thing, the stock drops, and the shareholders sue, saying =E2=80=
=9Cwe were tricked into buying your stock because you lied to us about not =
doing the bad thing.=E2=80=9D
This is I think a broadly correct description of how US securities class ac=
tions work in practice, but it is not a technically accurate description of=
 the law, and it is missing some nuance. For one thing, simply not mentioni=
ng a bad thing might not be enough to create securities-fraud liability: To=
 sue and win, shareholders will need to point to some misleading statement =
that the company=C2=A0did=C2=A0make. (So sexual harassment might be securit=
ies fraud if a company has a stated policy forbidding sexual harassment,=C2=
=A0or a risk factor in its annual report saying =E2=80=9Cwe rely on the ser=
vices of our chief executive officer and would have problems if he was a se=
xual harasser=E2=80=9D but not mentioning that he is.)
For another thing, there will be arguments about whether the misstatements =
or omissions were=C2=A0material=C2=A0to investors. If shareholders say =E2=
=80=9Cwe bought your stock because you lied to us and told us you were ethi=
cal, and we believed you,=E2=80=9D a plausible answer would be: =E2=80=9CNo=
 you didn=E2=80=99t, you didn=E2=80=99t care about our ethics, they don=E2=
=80=99t matter to our stock price and=C2=A0you were not actually defrauded.=
=E2=80=9D (This was   roughly the issue in a 2021 Supreme Court case about =
Goldman Sachs Group Inc. and the =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud=E2=
=80=9D theory.)
One way to synthesize these points is that there are some areas of corporat=
e behavior where a company can be=C2=A0good=C2=A0or=C2=A0bad, but these are=
as are not relevant to shareholders. That is:
=09The shareholders do not care about these areas of behavior; they do not =
evaluate whether a company behaves well or badly in these areas, and those =
questions do not inform their buying and selling decisions.=09Companies do =
not talk about these areas of behavior in their public filings.=09If it tur=
ns out that a company is bad in these areas, the stock doesn=E2=80=99t usua=
lly drop.

Like one bad thing that a public company could do is that its executives co=
uld have really bad fashion sense and dress really badly. (Not a high fashi=
on company I mean, just like a software company or whatever.) That would be=
 bad, in some aesthetic sense, but it would not be=C2=A0securities fraud. I=
nvestors would not make investing decisions based on executive fashion, the=
 company would not make any claims about it in its=C2=A0filings, and if a p=
hoto emerged of a badly dressed executive the stock would not drop.=C2=A0
These categories are fuzzy, though; there are some categories that investor=
s once did not care about but now=C2=A0do, some sorts of behavior that some=
times cause stock drops and sometimes don=E2=80=99t, some things that are o=
bliquely hinted at in securities filings. Sexual harassment scandals, for i=
nstance, seem more likely to cause business consequences and stock drops no=
w than they did 10 years ago, financial decision-makers   ask about them mo=
re frequently, and they are probably covered by companies=E2=80=99 disclose=
d ethics policies. You could argue that 10 years ago executive sexual haras=
sment was bad but not securities fraud, but now it is also securities fraud=
.
One rough way to think about the =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud=E2=
=80=9D theory is that, once upon a time,=C2=A0most=C2=A0sorts of corporate =
behavior fell into these categories =E2=80=94=C2=A0investors were presumed =
not to care about them, they weren=E2=80=99t discussed in filings, etc. =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and the=C2=A0only=C2=A0area that mattered was, like, financial =
results. =E2=80=9CSecurities fraud=E2=80=9D meant lying about earnings. And=
 then over time various areas of corporate behavior =E2=80=94=C2=A0executiv=
e ethics, cybersecurity, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0became=C2=A0things that compan=
ies disclosed and investors were presumed to care about, and so now shareho=
lders can sue companies if bad things happen in those areas.
Surely the biggest and most important example of this shift is ESG. Stereot=
yping very crudely, once upon a time investors did not care about the envir=
onmental, social and governance behavior of public companies, and now they =
care very much. For many investors, these are=C2=A0the most=C2=A0important =
factors; many investors have =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D (or =E2=80=9Csustainable=
,=E2=80=9D etc.) right in their fund names. And companies produce increasin=
g amounts of disclosure about ESG, in part because that=E2=80=99s what inve=
stors want but in large part because it=E2=80=99s what   regulators demand.
And so you could imagine 20 years ago thinking =E2=80=9Ccompanies produce f=
inancial statements, investors read the financial statements and use them t=
o make investing decisions, and if the financial statements are wrong that =
is securities fraud.=E2=80=9D And now you could imagine thinking =E2=80=9Cc=
ompanies produce ESG statements, investors read the ESG statements and use =
them to make investing decisions, and if the ESG statements are wrong that =
is securities fraud.=E2=80=9D The ESG statements haven=E2=80=99t=C2=A0repla=
ced=C2=A0the financial statements, but they exist parallel to them, and the=
y are =E2=80=A6=C2=A0perhaps not equally important, but certainly important=
 enough to produce   lots and lots of lawsuits:

Lawyers are bracing for an increase in ESG-related cases as corporate discl=
