10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">NYSE</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic problem of the stock market is that =
a lot of people want to buy a lot of stock, and a lot of people want to sel=
l a lot of stock, but not at the same=C2=A0time. I might want to buy 1,000 =
shares of Wells Fargo &amp; Co. stock, and you might want to sell 1,000 sha=
res of Wells Fargo five minutes from now. Our desires match up, but not in =
time, so we can=E2=80=99t trade with each other.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In theory, there are about three ways to deal =
with this.</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I could just wait. I could put in an =
order on the stock exchange to buy 1,000 shares, and then it could wait aro=
und for five minutes until you put in an order to sell 1,000 shares, and th=
en we could trade with each other. Sometimes it might take days. Lots of ma=
rkets work kind of like this, and there are aspects of this in the US stock=
 market,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-colo=
r: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0but this is mostly not how US public stock markets work. When I p=
ut in an order to buy Wells Fargo stock, it gets executed more or less imme=
diately.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There could be <em>market=
 makers</em>. Some people=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0banks,=C2=A0high-frequency el=
ectronic trading firms =E2=80=94=C2=A0could be willing to buy from all the =
sellers and sell to all the buyers, intermediating trades in time. I put in=
 my order to buy 1,000 shares, and some electronic market maker instantly s=
ells to me at $45.01 per share; five minutes later, you put in your order t=
o sell 1,000 shares, and the electronic market maker instantly buys from yo=
u at $44.99. We have each effectively paid a penny per share for =E2=80=9Ci=
mmediacy,=E2=80=9D the service that the market maker provided of letting us=
 trade instantly instead of waiting to find each other. The market maker is=
 in some sense not a real investor like you and me, and it will not general=
ly have some deeply informed view on the value of the stock: Its job is to =
buy and sell quickly, turn over its inventory, and get paid the spread betw=
een the $45.01 it charges me and the $44.99 it pays you.<a class=3D"footnot=
e-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; =
display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The exchange could get =
us all together at the same time. The stock exchange could say: =E2=80=9CHe=
y, everybody who wants to buy or sell Wells Fargo shares, we=E2=80=99re gon=
na do a big share swap at 9:30 a.m. tomorrow. Send in your orders, and we=
=E2=80=99ll match them up and let everyone trade at the same price at the s=
ame time.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Method 2 is sort of the standard paradigm for =
how the US stock market works. It is sometimes called a =E2=80=9Ccentral li=
mit order book,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CCLOB.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-ind=
ex" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displ=
ay: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It has its controversies, and lots of the market-structure stuff =
we talk about around here =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/30358593.259449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9v=
cGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDUvcm9iaW5ob29kLWdhbWVzdG9wLXNhZ2EtcHJlc3N=
1cmVzLXBheW1lbnQtZm9yLW9yZGVyLWZsb3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEyNTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdX=
RtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTI1JnV0b=
V9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe63717b6" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">paym=
ent for order flow</a> and dark pools and flash boys and blah blah blah =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0has to do with that process of market makers intermediating tra=
des in time.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I won=E2=80=99t discuss those controversies he=
re, but I do want to mention one complaint that people sometimes have, whic=
h is that liquidity in the stock market is somehow=C2=A0illusory or fleetin=
g or =E2=80=9Cnot real.=E2=80=9D Part of what this means is that, if=C2=A0t=
he national best bid and offer for Wells Fargo is $44.99/$45.01,=C2=A0you c=
ould go to a market maker and buy Wells Fargo for $45.01, or sell it for $4=
4.99, but you couldn=E2=80=99t buy or sell very=C2=A0<em>much=C2=A0</em>of =
it. The way the CLOB works is that market makers post limit orders at the e=
xchange; each market maker will say =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll buy 100 shares of=
 Wells Fargo at $44.99, and 200 more at $44.98, and 300 more at $44.95,=E2=
=80=9D etc. And then when you come in with a market order to sell, the exch=
ange looks at the limit orders it has on the book, and goes through them in=
 price order to execute your trade. So if you want to sell 100 shares, you =
trade at $44.99. If you want to sell 1,000 shares, you trade some at $44.99=
 and maybe some at lower prices. If you want to sell 100,000 shares, you mi=
ght run through=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em>of the orders that the market makers=
 have put on the order book. You might sell some at, like, $44, and then de=
scend into weird territory. Maybe some hedge fund put in an order to buy at=
 $20 and forgot about it, and you end up selling to them at $20.<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point is that the limit order book does no=
t represent the true economic supply and demand for a stock. It just repres=
ents the supply and demand for the stock=C2=A0<em>right now</em>, mainly fr=
om risk-averse high-frequency electronic market makers. If you want to sell=
 100,000 shares, you break that up into smaller orders so as not to scare o=
ff the market makers, you do it over some period of time, and eventually en=
ough people will want to buy that you=E2=80=99ll be able to sell at a reaso=
nable price. There will be some price impact of your trading =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0you can=E2=80=99t sell 100,000 shares at $44.99; supply and demand matte=
r =E2=80=94=C2=A0but you won=E2=80=99t sell at $20, either.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But every so often a trader at a big instituti=
onal investing firm=C2=A0will put in an order to sell 100,000 shares, and i=
nstead of hitting the =E2=80=9Cbreak this into small orders and sell over 8=
 hours=E2=80=9D button she will hit the =E2=80=9Cput in a market order to s=
ell all of this immediately=E2=80=9D button, and the stock will briefly cra=
sh as her trade eats through the entire order book and ends up printing at =
ridiculous prices. And then the stock will recover, because its value hasn=
=E2=80=99t really changed; it=E2=80=99s just that there were not enough ord=
ers resting on the book to execute that trade sensibly. This is sometimes c=
alled a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30358593.2=
59449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtM=
DMvY2l0aS1kaWQtYS1mbGFzaC1jcmFzaD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTI1MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1f=
bWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxMjUmdXRtX2N=
hbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7c445a68" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  =E2=
=80=9Cfat finger=E2=80=9D error</a>, because the only excuse for it is that=
 your finger is too big to hit the right button.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As I said, Method 2 is the main procedure, but=
=C2=A0Method 3 is also really important. In fact there=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</=
em>some obvious times when lots of people all want to trade at the same tim=
e: The US stock market=E2=80=99s main opening hours are 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m.=
, and people naturally gravitate toward trading at the open or the close, a=
t 9:30 or 4. And so the big listing exchanges, the <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30358593.259449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnlzZS5jb2=
0vcHVibGljZG9jcy9ueXNlL21hcmtldHMvbnlzZS9OWVNFX09wZW5pbmdfYW5kX0Nsb3NpbmdfQ=
XVjdGlvbnNfRmFjdF9TaGVldC5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB41668bec" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 New York Stock Exchange</a> and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/30358593.259449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmFzZGFxdHJhZGVyLmNvbS9jb250=
ZW50L1RlY2huaWNhbFN1cHBvcnQvVXNlckd1aWRlcy9UcmFkaW5nUHJvZHVjdHMvY3Jvc3Nlcy9=
vcGVuY2xvc2VxdWlja2d1aWRlLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb2c14164" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 Nasdaq</a>, run opening and closing auctions for the stocks they list. The=
 rough idea of the auction is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Everyone who wants to buy or sell stoc=
k at the open or the close puts in orders to buy or sell, in the minutes le=
ading up to 9:30 or 4.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some of tho=
se orders are market orders (=E2=80=9CI want to buy/sell stock at whatever =
the auction price ends up being=E2=80=9D), while others are limit orders (=
=E2=80=9CI want to buy stock in the auction if the price is $44.95 or less=
=E2=80=9D).</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The exchange=E2=80=99s=
 computers find a price that matches up the most orders and chooses that as=
 the auction price.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Everyone who p=
ut in an order to buy at the auction price or more (or with a market order)=
 buys, and everyone who put in an order=C2=A0to sell at the auction price o=
r less (or with a market order) sells.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <em>opening=C2=A0</em>auction is particula=
rly interesting. Intuitively, the stock market goes to bed at 4 p.m. and wa=
kes up at 9:30 a.m. the next day.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footn=
ote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !i=
mportant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"=
>
<span>[5]</span>
</a> Stuff happens overnight: News breaks, companies announce earnings and =
mergers, fund managers and retail traders stay up all night reading researc=
h reports and decide to buy some stock in the morning. Most days, most stoc=
ks will open at a price that is pretty close to the price they closed at th=
e day before. But sometimes there will be big jumps: If a company=E2=80=99s=
 stock closes at 4 p.m. at $45 (i.e., the price in the closing auction is $=
45), and then it=C2=A0announces good or bad earnings at 4:15, it might open=
 at $50 or $40 the next morning (i.e., the price in the opening auction wil=
l be a lot higher or lower).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The opening auction is where the day=E2=80=99s=
=C2=A0<em>price discovery=C2=A0</em>happens: All the =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D=
 investors, pension managers and hedge funds and retail traders on Robinhoo=
d, have updated their views on value overnight, and then they meet at 9:30 =
in the opening auction and work out what the market-clearing price is.=C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Notice that in Method 3 you don=E2=80=99t real=
ly need market makers: All the =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D buyers who want to ow=
n the stock show up to buy, and all the =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D sellers who =
own stock and want to get rid of it show up to sell, and they all trade at =
the same time at a price that balances their supply and demand. Market make=
rs are necessary in a central=C2=A0limit order book, because they intermedi=
ate between real buyers and sellers who want to trade at different times, b=
ut the auction solves that problem in a different way.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, market makers probably don=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>to trade in the opening auction. A market maker does =
not have a deeply informed view about the fundamental value of a stock; it =
just tries to turn over inventory quickly and do trades at pretty close to =
the previous trade. At 9:30 a.m.,=C2=A0<em>there is no previous trade</em>.=
<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: trans=
parent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The market is just waking up, there is news to digest from the pr=
evious 17.5 hours without trading, and lots of informed fundamental investo=
rs have been digesting it and are now trying to figure out the right price.=
 The market makers have no advantage, and will want to stay out of the way.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so there=E2=80=99s an opening auction amon=
g mostly real investors, and it sets the opening price, and a bunch of shar=
es trade at that price, and then a millisecond later normal trading starts.=
 And when normal trading starts, the market makers put in their orders to b=
uy and sell stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0probably to buy it for about a penny less =
than the opening price, and to sell it for about a penny more than the open=
ing price =E2=80=94=C2=A0and regular orders arrive to trade with them, and =
the price moves around with supply and demand, and the market operates with=
 a central limit order book for the next 6.5 hours.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yesterday the New York Stock Exchange made one=
 teeny little mistake: <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/30358593.259449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9kb3plbnMtb2Ytbn=
lzZS1zdG9ja3MtaGFsdGVkLWluLW9wZW5pbmctbWludXRlcy1hZnRlci13aWxkLXByaWNlLXN3a=
W5ncy0xMTY3NDU4NTk2Mj9tb2Q9aXRwX3dzaiZydT15YWhvbw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
b022279e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;"> It forgot to do some opening auctions</a>.</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A technical glitch at the New York Stock Excha=
nge on Tuesday briefly caused wild price swings and a temporary trading fre=
eze in stocks of major companies such as Exxon Mobil Corp., McDonald=E2=80=
=99s Corp. and Walmart Inc.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hundreds of stocks experienced erroneous price=
s as a result of the incident, the biggest snafu to hit a U.S. stock exchan=
ge in several years, according to a spreadsheet of affected securities rele=
ased by the NYSE.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The NYSE said in an accompanying notice to tra=
ders that, due to a =E2=80=9Csystem issue,=E2=80=9D it had failed to carry =
out an opening auction in a number of stocks. The opening auction is the cr=
itical process at 9:30 a.m. ET each day that determines the official, begin=
ning-of-day prices for stocks listed on the exchange.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Without a reliable official opening price, som=
e stocks traded at unusually low or high prices as the trading day began. T=
hat in turn caused sharp price swings, triggering trading halts under marke=
t rules designed to curb extreme volatility.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a real mess,=E2=80=9D sa=
id Dennis Dick, founder of Triple D Trading, a proprietary trading firm. =
=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve traded for 22 years, and I=E2=80=99ve never seen the =
opening cross at NYSE go haywire.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Intuitively, what seems to have happened is th=
at if you woke up at 7 a.m. and put in an order with your broker to buy 500=
 shares of Walmart at the open, and then you went off to work at your job a=
nd forgot about it, your broker probably put in a market order to buy 500 s=
hares in the opening auction. And then there was no opening auction. So you=
r order got sent to the central limit order book to execute as a normal tra=
de, instead of executing in the opening auction.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are two big problems with that. One is t=
hat, at 9:30:00, the central limit order book is <em>empty</em>. The market=
 makers who intermediate trades in time are=C2=A0<em>waiting=C2=A0</em>on t=
he opening auction to populate the order book; if the auction doesn=E2=80=
=99t happen and CLOB trading opens anyway, there=E2=80=99s no one there to =
buy from the sellers and sell to the buyers. I mean, not literally no one =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0somebody has put in limit orders to buy and sell =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but the professional electronic market makers whose job it is to post=
 prices in a tight range have not really shown up yet in meaningful size. S=
o the order book is thinly populated, and any new orders =E2=80=94=C2=A0lik=
e your order to buy 500 shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0can move the price more.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other problem is that the=C2=A0orders in t=
he opening auction can be=C2=A0<em>big</em>. If you are looking to buy 10,0=
00 shares at the market price at 11:15 a.m., you will break that into small=
er orders and be tactical about how you trade it, because you know that sen=
ding a 10,000-share market order can crash through the order book and get y=
ou a terrible price. But if you are looking to buy 10,000 shares at the mar=
ket price at 9:30 a.m., you might just put in a 10,000-share market-on-open=
 order, because you know that lots of people want to trade in the opening a=
uction and so you will get a good price.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If there is no auction, and=C2=A0your 10,000-s=
hare market order gets sent to the regular order book instead, then NYSE ha=
s effectively fat-fingered you. It sent your <em>unusually large</em> order=
 into an <em>unusually thin</em> order book. And so the stock crashes, or s=
oars, depending on whether you are buying or selling.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The details=C2=A0are still a little vague and =
I am being approximate here. You might ask: =E2=80=9CWell, if there are a l=
ot of orders to buy a lot of shares and a lot of orders to sell a lot of sh=
ares and they all got sent to the regular order book at the same time, woul=
dn=E2=80=99t they trade with each other and cancel out and lead to pretty n=
ormal prices,=E2=80=9D but that is apparently not quite=C2=A0how it works. =
The thing about an auction is that all the orders execute at once; in a cen=
tral limit order book they execute in some sequential=C2=A0order. You could=
 imagine NYSE looking at its list of orders, seeing a market sell order, ex=
ecuting it against the few resting limit buy orders, crashing the price dow=
n, looking at the next order, seeing a market buy order, and executing it a=
gainst the few resting limit sell orders, shooting the price right back up =
again. And that=E2=80=99s how you get =E2=80=9Csharp price swings, triggeri=
ng trading halts.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway in the grand scheme of things this does=
n=E2=80=99t matter: Yesterday=E2=80=99s opening=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>matc=
h buyers and sellers, over time, and find the market price, just in a harro=
wing and chaotic way. If you traded at the wrong price, it mattered to you,=
 since you made or lost money, though a lot of those trades <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30358593.259449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMjQvbnlzZS1zYXlzLWNlcnRhaW4t=
b3JkZXJzLXdpbGwtYmUtY2FuY2VsZWQtYWZ0ZXItc3lzdGVtLWlzc3VlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjU=
yM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV=
90ZXJtPTIzMDEyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1=
eaa4407" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">  will be busted</a> because they were =E2=80=9Cclearly er=
roneous.=E2=80=9D NYSE has a sensible market structure for its 9:30:00 a.m.=
 trading, and a sensible market structure for its 9:30:01 a.m. trading, and=
 they are=C2=A0<em>very different</em>, and if you mix them up you get a me=
ss.</p>
