XR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTI1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cBe2568ef7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  say</a> that every bad thing that a public =
company does is also securities fraud. It does the bad thing, it does not i=
mmediately tell shareholders about the bad thing, later the shareholders fi=
nd out about the bad thing, the stock drops, and the shareholders sue, sayi=
ng =E2=80=9Cwe were tricked into buying your stock because you lied to us a=
bout not doing the bad thing.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is I think a broadly correct description =
of how US securities class actions work in practice, but it is not a techni=
cally accurate description of the law, and it is missing some nuance. For o=
ne thing, <em>simply not mentioning</em> a bad thing might not be enough to=
 create securities-fraud liability: To sue and win, shareholders will need =
to point to some misleading statement that the company=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</=
em>make. (So sexual harassment might be securities fraud if a company has a=
 stated policy forbidding sexual harassment,=C2=A0or a risk factor in its a=
nnual report saying =E2=80=9Cwe rely on the services of our chief executive=
 officer and would have problems if he was a sexual harasser=E2=80=9D but n=
ot mentioning that he is.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For another thing, there will be arguments abo=
ut whether the misstatements or omissions were=C2=A0<em>material=C2=A0</em>=
to investors. If shareholders say =E2=80=9Cwe bought your stock because you=
 lied to us and told us you were ethical, and we believed you,=E2=80=9D a p=
lausible answer would be: =E2=80=9CNo you didn=E2=80=99t, you didn=E2=80=99=
t care about our ethics, they don=E2=80=99t matter to our stock price and=
=C2=A0you were not actually defrauded.=E2=80=9D (This was <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30358593.259449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMjIvZXZlcnl0aGluZy1zdGlsbC=
1taWdodC1iZS1zZWN1cml0aWVzLWZyYXVkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0b=
V9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDEyNSZ1dG1f=
Y2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6b7c9f28" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  rou=
ghly the issue</a> in a 2021 Supreme Court case about Goldman Sachs Group I=
nc. and the =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud=E2=80=9D theory.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to synthesize these points is that the=
re are some areas of corporate behavior where a company can be=C2=A0<em>goo=
d=C2=A0</em>or=C2=A0<em>bad</em>, but these areas are <em>not relevant to s=
hareholders</em>. That is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The shareholders do not care about th=
ese areas of behavior; they do not evaluate whether a company behaves well =
or badly in these areas, and those questions do not inform their buying and=
 selling decisions.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Companies do n=
ot talk about these areas of behavior in their public filings.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If it turns out that a company is bad in these=
 areas, the stock doesn=E2=80=99t usually drop.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Like one bad thing that a public company could=
 do is that its executives could have really bad fashion sense and dress re=
ally badly. (Not a high fashion company I mean, just like a software compan=
y or whatever.) That would be <em>bad</em>, in some aesthetic sense, but it=
 would not be=C2=A0<em>securities fraud</em>. Investors would not make inve=
sting decisions based on executive fashion, the company would not make any =
claims about it in its=C2=A0filings, and if a photo emerged of a badly dres=
sed executive the stock would not drop.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These categories are fuzzy, though; there are =
some categories that investors once did not care about but now=C2=A0do, som=
e sorts of behavior that sometimes cause stock drops and sometimes don=E2=
=80=99t, some things that are obliquely hinted at in securities filings. Se=
xual harassment scandals, for instance, seem more likely to cause business =
consequences and stock drops now than they did 10 years ago, financial deci=
sion-makers <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/303585=
93.259449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtM=
DgtMDIvLW1ldG9vLWlzLWEtZHVlLWRpbGlnZW5jZS1pc3N1ZS1ub3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEyNTIz=
X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3R=
lcm09MjMwMTI1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBad5c=
686d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">  ask about them more frequently</a>, and they are probably c=
overed by companies=E2=80=99 disclosed ethics policies. You could argue tha=
t 10 years ago executive sexual harassment was bad but not securities fraud=
, but now it is also securities fraud.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One rough way to think about the =E2=80=9Cever=
ything is securities fraud=E2=80=9D theory is that, once upon a time,=C2=A0=
<em>most=C2=A0</em>sorts of corporate behavior fell into these categories =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0investors were presumed not to care about them, they weren=
=E2=80=99t discussed in filings, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the=C2=A0<em>only=
=C2=A0</em>area that mattered was, like, financial results. =E2=80=9CSecuri=
ties fraud=E2=80=9D meant lying about earnings. And then over time various =
areas of corporate behavior =E2=80=94=C2=A0executive ethics, cybersecurity,=
 etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0<em>became=C2=A0</em>things that companies disclosed a=
nd investors were presumed to care about, and so now shareholders can sue c=
ompanies if bad things happen in those areas.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Surely the biggest and most important example =
of this shift is ESG. Stereotyping very crudely, once upon a time investors=
 did not care about the environmental, social and governance behavior of pu=
blic companies, and now they care very much. For many investors, these are=
=C2=A0<em>the most=C2=A0</em>important factors; many investors have =E2=80=
=9CESG=E2=80=9D (or =E2=80=9Csustainable,=E2=80=9D etc.) right in their fun=
d names. And companies produce increasing amounts of disclosure about ESG, =
in part because that=E2=80=99s what investors want but in large part becaus=
e it=E2=80=99s what <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/30358593.259449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMjItMDMtMjIvdGhlLXNlYy13aWxsLXJlZ3VsYXRlLWNsaW1hdGU_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEyNTIz=
X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3R=
lcm09MjMwMTI1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa702=
572a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">  regulators demand</a>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so you could imagine 20 years ago thinking=
 =E2=80=9Ccompanies produce financial statements, investors read the financ=
ial statements and use them to make investing decisions, and if the financi=
al statements are wrong that is securities fraud.=E2=80=9D And now you coul=
d imagine thinking =E2=80=9Ccompanies produce ESG statements, investors rea=
d the ESG statements and use them to make investing decisions, and if the E=
SG statements are wrong that is securities fraud.=E2=80=9D The ESG statemen=
ts haven=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>replaced=C2=A0</em>the financial statements, bu=
t they exist parallel to them, and they are =E2=80=A6=C2=A0perhaps not equa=
lly important, but certainly important enough to produce <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30358593.259449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMjUvY2xhc3MtYWN0aW9uLXdhdmUtaXM=
tY29taW5nLWZvci1lc2ctY2xhaW1zLWdyZWVuLWluc2lnaHQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEyNTIzX01PTk=
VZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09M=
jMwMTI1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe51abedb" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">  lots and lots of lawsuits</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lawyers are bracing for an increase in ESG-rel=
ated cases as corporate disclosure requirements stiffen around the world.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A survey by the law firm Norton Rose Fulbright=
 found that 28% of more than 430 general counsel and in-house litigation le=
aders said their so-called ESG dispute exposure increased in 2022, and 24% =
expect it to deepen over the next 12 months. The key reasons are the absenc=
e of clear environmental, social and governance metrics and requirements, a=
nd the heightened regulatory scrutiny on the importance of ESG.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The issue has joined employment and labor disp=
utes,=C2=A0cybersecurity and data protection in what Norton Rose refers to =
as =E2=80=9Cclass-action areas of future concern.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The growing attention of corporate litigators =
in industries ranging from financial services to technology corresponds wit=
h the growing tide of class actions tied to greenwashing. This is partly du=
e to the California=E2=80=99s plaintiffs=E2=80=99 bar having =E2=80=9Cfigur=
ed out the blueprint for how to bring these cases,=E2=80=9D according to No=
rton Rose. In a nutshell, this means companies that put out generalized ESG=
 statements will sometimes find themselves as targets in product-specific c=
ases.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you make a product that is bad for the envi=
ronment, that didn=E2=80=99t use to be securities fraud, but it sure is now=
.</p>
