<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For a long time, most floating-rate corporate=
=C2=A0loans in the US were priced off Libor, the London interbank offered r=
ate, a publicly reported index of bank borrowing costs. A company would bor=
row money at Libor plus some spread, with the spread compensating its lende=
rs for the credit risk they take by lending to the company. A loan would ha=
ve an interest rate like =E2=80=9CLibor + 300,=E2=80=9D and then every thre=
e months you=E2=80=99d look at what three-month dollar Libor was and add 30=
0 basis points to it and that would be the interest rate on the loan. And t=
hen three months later you=E2=80=99d do it again.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Then Libor fell into disrepute, and regulators=
 made a big effort to get rid of Libor and replace it with other, more reli=
able rates. In the US, this <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/30358593.259449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmV3eW9ya2ZlZC5vcmcvYXJyYy9zb2ZyL=
XRyYW5zaXRpb24/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe19d6a0b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> meant mainly SOF=
R</a>, the Secured Overnight Financing Rate. (And other, longer-term rates =
that are derived from SOFR: SOFR is, as the name suggests, an overnight rat=
e, but you can get things like =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/30358593.259449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY21lZ3JvdXAuY29tL21hc=
mtldC1kYXRhL2NtZS1ncm91cC1iZW5jaG1hcmstYWRtaW5pc3RyYXRpb24vdGVybS1zb2ZyLmh0=
bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4e9b2719" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">3-month term SOFR</a>=E2=80=
=9D from derivatives markets.) So now you could have a loan with an interes=
t rate like =E2=80=9CSOFR + 300,=E2=80=9D and every three months you=E2=80=
=99d look at three-month SOFR and etc. Same basic idea, different index.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For our purposes, one important fact about SOF=
R is that it is=C2=A0<em>lower=C2=A0</em>than Libor: SOFR is a secured rate=
 (lending against Treasury collateral), Libor is an unsecured rate (lending=
 to banks against their credit), and it should be cheaper to borrow secured=
 than unsecured. Exactly how much lower SOFR is than Libor on any particula=
r day depends on economic conditions, market moods, etc. But, generally, lo=
wer.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing this means is that if you are a comp=
any and you want to borrow money, your bank might recommend that you get a =
loan priced off SOFR rather than Libor. SOFR is the way of the future, Libo=
r is in disrepute and slowly being phased out, the market wants SOFR, so yo=
u get a SOFR loan. The bank will quote you some price like SOFR + 300, and =
that=E2=80=99s the loan you=E2=80=99ll get. Libor won=E2=80=99t even enter =
into it. The price =E2=80=94=C2=A0the spread, the 300 basis points you pay =
over SOFR =E2=80=94=C2=A0is just set by market demand for the loan.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another thing it means is that if you are a co=
mpany and you <em>already=C2=A0</em>have a loan and the loan is priced at L=
ibor + 300, you might want to=C2=A0<em>change=C2=A0</em>the terms of the lo=
an, to make it priced off of SOFR. SOFR is the future, Libor is going away,=
 etc., why not update your loan to use the modern index? But SOFR is=C2=A0<=
em>lower=C2=A0</em>than Libor. Three-month Libor is about 4.82% today; if y=
our loan is priced at Libor + 300, you=E2=80=99re paying something like 7.8=
2% interest. Three-month term SOFR is about 4.67% today, 15 basis points lo=
wer than Libor. If you want to switch your Libor loan into a SOFR loan, tod=
ay, you would need to make your Libor + 300 loan into a SOFR + 315 loan to =
make the actual interest payments the same. If you kept the spread the same=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you switched from Libor + 300 to SOFR + 300 =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0then you=E2=80=99d be paying less. Your lenders wouldn=E2=80=99t like th=
at.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In practice the way you do this is by adding a=
 =E2=80=9Ccredit spread adjustment=E2=80=9D to the loan: You keep the thing=
 called the =E2=80=9Cspread=E2=80=9D the same, at 300 basis points, and you=
 add a new contractual term called a =E2=80=9Ccredit spread adjustment=E2=
=80=9D intended to compensate for the switch from Libor to SOFR. Then your =
interest rate is (1) SOFR plus (2) the spread plus (3) the credit spread ad=
justment. And there is sort of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/30358593.259449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydG=
ljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMjQvZmVkLXVwLWNsby1idXllcnMtcHVzaC1tYW5hZ2Vycy10by1yZWplY=
3QtdGVybXMtb2YtbGlib3Itc3dpdGNoP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9t=
ZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDEyNSZ1dG1fY2F=
tcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB025a96fb" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a stand=
ard for what that is</a>, based on the average difference between Libor and=
 SOFR over time:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Alternative Reference Rates Co=
mmittee, the Federal Reserve backed group in charge of overseeing the Libor=
 transition in the US, recommended borrowers provide adjustments of 11 basi=
s points and 26 basis points for loans tied to one- and three-month Libor, =
respectively.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now. You could imagine different ways that thi=
s transition might go. You could imagine =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30358593.259449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDgtMjcvdGhlLWxpYm9yLWNoYW5nZS1p=
cy1jb21pbmc_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEyNTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1=
fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTI1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dW=
Zm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB224407a7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">and I did, once</a> =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0banks calling up borrowers and saying =E2=80=9Chey, I see you have a =
Libor loan, let me switch you into a shiny new SOFR loan,=E2=80=9D and doin=
g that in a way that made the banks money. You have a complicated trade, yo=
u restructure it into a different complicated trade, that=E2=80=99s just a =
classic place for a bank to make money. With a loan I am not sure there is =
too much complicated opportunity, but I guess you can add a 30 basis point =
credit spread adjustment and charge a fee too.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it could go the other way. You could imagi=
ne the borrowers calling up the banks and saying=C2=A0 =E2=80=9CI want my L=
ibor loan to be SOFR=E2=80=9D and the banks saying =E2=80=9Csure, but we ne=
ed to add an 11 basis point credit spread adjustment=E2=80=9D and the borro=
wers saying =E2=80=9Cwhat, no, that sounds like a scam, I want the same loa=
n but with SOFR,=E2=80=9D and the banks saying =E2=80=9Cugh fine I guess wh=
atever.=E2=80=9D That is not my usual experience of banks. On the other han=
d a lot of leveraged corporate loans are not held by=C2=A0<em>banks</em>, p=
er se, but by collateralized loan obligations, and I guess their negotiatin=
g tactics are different? Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Carmen Arroyo and Paula S=
eligson <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30358593.2=
59449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMjQvZ=
mVkLXVwLWNsby1idXllcnMtcHVzaC1tYW5hZ2Vycy10by1yZWplY3QtdGVybXMtb2YtbGlib3It=
c3dpdGNoP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3N=
vdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDEyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC025a96fb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> report</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Buyers of the riskiest slice of collateralized=
 loan obligations are stepping up efforts to ensure the transition from Lib=
or doesn=E2=80=99t end up costing them millions of dollars in potential ret=
urns.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Roughly 70 CLO equity investors attended a cal=
l hosted by Eagle Point Credit Management earlier this month where particip=
ants discussed pushing CLO managers to advocate harder for their economic i=
nterests, multiple firms that attended the meeting confirmed to Bloomberg.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They=E2=80=99re particularly frustrated that s=
ome borrowers have been able to switch their existing loans to the Secured =
Overnight Financing Rate without including an adjustment blessed by industr=
y officials that=E2=80=99s meant to compensate for the fact that SOFR consi=
stently prints below Libor, allowing companies to reap significant savings =
at their expense. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe regulators did not intend for the=
 Libor-SOFR transition to create a windfall for private equity sponsors and=
 loan issuers,=E2=80=9D said Dan Ko, principal and portfolio manager at Eag=
le Point.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is more from Seligson <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30358593.259449/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMjAvbGV2ZXJhZ2VkLWxvYW4taW52ZXN0=
b3JzLWxvc2luZy1taWxsaW9ucy1vbi1saWJvci10by1zb2ZyLXN3aXRjaC1maWdodC1iYWNrP2N=
tcGlkPUJCRDAxMjUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZX=
dzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDEyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB5521ed0f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> last month</a>. Basically borrowers ask t=
o amend their Libor loans to make them SOFR loans with the same spreads and=
 no adjustments, and lenders are like =E2=80=9Csure whatever I guess=E2=80=
=9D:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For months, lenders largely let them get away =
with it.=C2=A0The reasons varied. Opinions differed among investors on whic=
h deals were worth fighting over, and some saw diminishing returns from qui=
bbling over a few basis points when the Fed was jacking up rates.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Moreover, they simply weren=E2=80=99t organize=
d enough to block the proposals, especially those tied to loans with so-cal=
led negative consent clauses, which comprise about 30% of the market, accor=
ding to Covenant Review data. Those clauses, which Allied Universal had, re=
quire more than half of creditors to actively vote to reject amendments, in=
 contrast to a typical loan where debtholders must vote yes for an amendmen=
t to pass.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One broad point here is that the traditional w=
ay to think about bank lending is that the=C2=A0<em>lenders=C2=A0</em>are s=
ophisticated finance professionals and the=C2=A0<em>borrowers=C2=A0</em>are=
 not: Banks are in the business of making and pricing and negotiating loans=
; corporate borrowers are in the business of retailing or software or manuf=
acturing or whatever. The banks are repeat players who know the loans insid=
e and out and can negotiate in ways that consistently advantage them; the c=
orporate borrowers have to take what the banks give them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in modern leveraged finance it is almost t=
he opposite? Lenders are not (mainly) banks but CLOs, vehicles with weird i=
ncentives and coordination problems. Borrowers meanwhile are not mainly wid=
get manufacturers but, as Ko says, =E2=80=9Cprivate equity sponsors,=E2=80=
=9D sophisticated repeat players who are good at making money by extracting=
 it from lenders. If regulators decide to change how bank loans work, tradi=
tionally that should be good for the banks. But now it=E2=80=99s good for t=
he borrowers.</p>
