f the $13 billion in debt tacked onto Twitter Inc. for his buyout of the co=
mpany, people familiar with the matter said. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In mid-December, Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s team reach=
ed out to new and existing backers about raising new equity capital at the =
original Twitter takeover price.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s advisers had hoped to reach=
 a deal to raise cash at the initial takeover price by the end of 2022, acc=
ording to an email sent to prospective investors at the time. However, some=
 prospective backers said they balked at the terms, given concerns about Tw=
itter=E2=80=99s financial performance. The Musk team didn=E2=80=99t specify=
 a funding amount or purpose for the fundraise in the email.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fidelity, one of the co-investors that backed =
Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s takeover of Twitter, has written down its stake in Twitt=
er by 56%, public filings show, suggesting Mr. Musk would face an uphill ba=
ttle raising funds at the original valuation from outside investors.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If he gets $6 billion in orders for a $3 billi=
on financing round at the original takeover price =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I don=E2=
=80=99t even know what to say. That would be amazing. He also testified tha=
t he has raised =E2=80=9Cmore money than anyone in history by a significant=
 margin,=E2=80=9D so he=E2=80=99s good at raising money and has devoted fan=
s, but even for him this seems like a heavy lift.</p>
